    <div id="news">
        <div class="row">
        <div class="date">
              <h3 class="date">Feb 2025</h3>
          </div>
        <div class="news-item">
        Ruthe gave a talk entitled "Beyond Child-Directed Speech: Active Learning in Early Language Development" at the <a href="https://ruccs.rutgers.edu/talks/list-of-past-events/list.events/-?catids=35">Rutgers Center for Cognitive Science Colloquium Series.</a>
        <p style="margin-bottom:0rem"></p>
        
        With generous funding from the Eugene Lang College of Liberal Arts Dean's office, the lab welcomed its first research interns, Nathan Simon and Henri Winter!
        </div>
        </div>
    <div class="row">
          <div class="date">
              <h3 class="date"> Jan 2025 </h3>
          </div>
          <div class="news-item">
          <a href="https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfsifip0odlEWWE39Gu2UGZYMLOGCxKIoQneARHNNrjWd4vqg/viewform">We are accepting abstracts</a> for the second annual interdisciplinary early-career researcher conference.</p>

          This year's theme is <a href="https://event.newschool.edu/languageandmethod"><i>Language and Method</i></a>, asking:<p style="margin-bottom:-.1rem">
              <ul class="news-sublist" style="margin-bottom:-.5rem">
                <li> <i>What are the implications of methodological pluralism in the study of human language? Are any methods truly incompatible?</i></li>
                <li><i>Do methodological commitments divide disciplines? If so, are these divisions over- or under- exaggerated? Where is there common ground?</i></li>
                <li> <i>What is the relation between methodology and object of inquiry?</i></li>
              </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
    <div class="row">
          <div class="date">
              <h3 class="date"> Dec 2024 </h3>
          </div>
          <div class="news-item">
          Lab members Sydney Segal, Anna Mercier, Silver Litfin, and Alexandra Kahn received competitive Student Research Award funding for their proposal capturing embodied communication between Tseltal Maya infants and mothers.
          <p style="margin-bottom:0rem"></p>

          Lorraine Afflitto passed the defense for her proposed dissertation, "Infants' sensitivity to sartorial markers of ethnic identity" &#8212; congrats, Lorraine!
          <p style="margin-bottom:0rem"></p>

          Two lab projects were accepted to the <a href="https://www.srcd.org/event/srcd-2025-biennial-meeting">Biennial Meeting of the Society for Research in Child Development (#SRCD25)</a>, taking place in Minneapolis in May.
          </div>
        </div>
    <div class="row">
          <div class="date">
              <h3 class="date"> Nov 2024 </h3>
          </div>
          <div class="news-item">
          A second annual language conference was funded by the NSSR Dean's office! We're looking forward to building on the success of last year. 
          </div>
        </div>
    <div class="row">
          <div class="date">
              <h3 class="date"> Aug 2024 </h3>
          </div>
          <div class="news-item">
          Travis Stackow started as a first-year Psychology Ph.D. student in the <a href="https://www.newschool.edu/nssr/phd-cognitive-social-developmental-psychology/">Cognitive, Social, Developmental</a> area at NSSR!
          </div>
        </div>
      <div class="row">
          <div class="date">
              <h3 class="date"> July 2024 </h3>
          </div>
          <div class="news-item">
          Ruthe spoke about hearing caregivers' interactions with their deaf and hearing children at the <a href="https://iascl2024.com">International Association for the Study of Child Language</a> in Prague.
          </div>
        </div>
      <div class="row">
          <div class="date">
              <h3 class="date"> May 2024 </h3>
          </div>
          <div class="news-item">
          Ana Hafley and Nivi Gargi, senior capstone students in the lab, graduated from Lang &#8212; congratulations, both!
          </div>
        </div>
      <div class="row">
          <div class="date">
              <h3 class="date"> April 2024 </h3>
          </div>
          <div class="news-item">
          The <a href="https://event.newschool.edu/languageconference"><i>Language: What is it Good For?</i></a> conference was a success, with graduate student scholars presenting <a href="/events">work from diverse disciplinary perspectives</a> &#8212; including linguistics, psychology, philosophy, anthropology, literary theory, cultural studies, performance studies, and design.<p style="margin-bottom:-.1rem"></p>

          NSSR students Travis Stackow, Gen Tsudaka, Matteo Burrell, Sydney Segal, Abby Merrick, and Zach Sauer chaired panels. Jay Krizan, Arnold Yiu, and Pip Yap made sure everything went smoothly &#8212; and the lab (specifically Ruthe, Travis, Gen, Sydney, Simone, and Jay) made the food for the conference! 
          </div>
        </div>
       <div class="row">
          <div class="date">
              <h3 class="date"> Feb 2024 </h3>
          </div>
          <div class="news-item">
          We are excited to be receiving abstracts for the graduate student conference entitled <a href="https://event.newschool.edu/languageconference"><i>Language: What is it Good For?</i></a><p style="margin-bottom:-.1rem"></p>

          <a href="https://forms.gle/SZ6dzqKjW9w6spW5A">There is still time to submit work</a>  that speaks to: 
              <ul class="news-sublist" style="margin-bottom:-.5rem">
                <li> <i>Contributors to communicative success</i> & characterizing communicative ‘failure’ or misunderstanding</li>
                <li> <i>Interlocutor effects in conversation</i>: how do different interlocutors make different conversations possible? How do listeners influence speakers?</li>
                <li> <i>The interplay of language structure, multimodal cues (e.g., gesture), context, biology, & history</i> in linguistic interpretation, online processing, and language production </li>
                <li> <i>Competing disciplinary conceptualizations of language</i> (& their implications), with opportunities for interdisciplinary insight.</li>
              </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
